{"title_page": "Airfone", "text_new": "{{short description|Air-ground radiotelephone service}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2009}}\n{{Missing information|technical details and payment methods|date=March 2013}}\n}}\n\n'''Airfone''' was an [[air-ground radiotelephone service]] developed by [[MCI Communications|MCI]] founder [[John D. Goeken]], and operated under the names ''Airfone'', ''GTE Airfone'', and [[Verizon]] Airfone. Airfone allowed passengers to make telephone calls (later including data modem service) in-flight. Airfone handsets were often located in the middle airliner seatbacks, with two handsets per row for 6-wide coach seating configurations, and more or less depending on the aircraft layout and fare class. First class cabins typically had one handset per seat. Some planes had one or more bulkhead mounted phone stations with cordless handsets that the passengers could use, instead of the multiple wired handsets.  Airfone phone calls were usually quite expensive compared to ground-based telephone calls, costing $3.99 per call and $4.99 per minute in 2006.\n\nThe original Airfone main office and [[network operations center]] are located at 2809 Butterfield Rd, Oak Brook, Illinois. The [[network operations center]] remains at this location.<ref>[https://local.google.com/maps?q=Airfone+IL&hl=en&ll=41.842791,-87.987614&spn=0.011669,0.024054&sll=27.698638,-83.804601&sspn=14.175034,24.631348&hq=Airfone&hnear=Illinois&t=m&z=16 Airfone map location.]</ref>\n\n[[Bell Mobility]] used the Airfone technology on [[Air Canada]] flights, but branded its service as Skytel (no relation to the Verizon-owned paging firm of the same name).\n\n== Use==\nCalls were often discounted or free for customers of airplane-based catalogs like [[Sky Mall]], and [[Verizon Wireless]] subscribers could pay $10 per month and 10 cents a call or a flat 69 cents per call with no monthly fee. Airfone could be used for very slow modem calls, and attempts at data service were made in 2003 and 2004 using an on-board email proxy server.\n\nMany of the in-flight calls made by victims of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] were made over Airfone and Air One.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/ |title=Complete 9/11 Commission Report |date=2004 |author=National Commission on Terrorist Attacks Upon the United States |accessdate=2016-06-07}}</ref>\n\nAirfone's primary competitor was Air One, operated by [[AT&T Wireless]] division Claircom Communications Group, and was available onboard [[American Airlines]], [[Northwest Airlines]], and select [[Delta Air Lines]] aircraft.  The Air One service was discontinued in 2002.\n\n== History ==\n===Development===\nThe Airfone was originated by [[John D. Goeken]] (who also founded [[MCI Communications]] and [[Florists' Transworld Delivery|FTD]]'s Mercury Network) in the 1970s. [[Western Union]] purchased a fifty percent share in Airfone in 1981 and sold to [[GTE]] in 1986 for [[United States dollar|US]]$39&nbsp;million cash.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bechtel|first=Warren|title=Western Union Chronology of Events - 1851 -1995|url=http://www.westernunionalumni.com/history.htm|accessdate=2008-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207045921/http://www.westernunionalumni.com/history.htm|archive-date=2012-02-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Delta Air Lines]] offered the United States's first public air-to-ground telephone system with Airfone.\n\nThe first iteration of Airfone service only permitted air-to-ground calls and frequently dropped calls. A new generation dubbed GenStar was developed jointly by GTE and [[Teknekron Corporation#Successes|IEX Corp.]] in 1992. IEX developed the software, which ran on hardware built by [[Stratus Technologies#History|Stratus Computers]]. GenStar introduced the capacity for airborne nodes to also receive calls, and for connections to be [[Handover|handed over]] between ground cells as the aircraft moved through them, reducing dropped calls. Handsets also gained screens and jacks for fax transmissions.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Belden | first = Tom | title = New Phone System Reaches Passengers During Their Flights | work = The Philadelphia Inquirer | location = Philadelphia | accessdate = 2012-10-04 | date = 1993-12-20\n| url = http://articles.philly.com/1993-12-20/business/25940877_1_gte-airfone-new-phone-system-genstar }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | pages = 1F | last = Steinert-Threlkeld | first = Tom | title = GTE Airfone responds to higher calling | work = The Dallas Morning News | accessdate = 2012-10-04 | date = 1992-02-08 | url = http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/NewsBank/0ED3D219988FC03A/49A2E19BE58747EE91F5ACB8D85A7A48?s_lang }}</ref>\n\n===Demise===\nThe head of the Airfone division told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2004 that only two to three people use the Airfone service per flight.  In May and June 2006, the frequencies ([[Bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]]) over which Airfone operated were sold at auction by the [[U.S. Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) to two new licenseholders, [[Aircell]] and [[LiveTV]].<ref>[https://www.engadget.com/2008/06/09/jetblues-livetv-unit-to-snatch-up-verizons-airfone-network/ JetBlue's LiveTV unit to snatch up Verizon's Airfone network.  Darren Murph Jun 9th, 2008 8:12 AM]</ref> Under the terms of the FCC order that authorized the auction, Verizon received a non-renewable license until 2010, but had two years from the end of the auction to redeploy Airfone to use less bandwidth and share spectrum with one of the license winners.\n\nOn June 23, 2006, [[Verizon]] Communications, Airfone's parent company, announced that they would be discontinuing their Airfone service on all commercial flights by the end of 2006. They cited the declining use of the service, as well as a desire to focus on their key businesses: broadband, wireless and wireline services. Airfone service is currently{{When|date=June 2009}} installed on 1000 aircraft belonging to [[United Airlines]] and [[Continental Airlines]]. [[US Airways]] and [[Delta Air Lines]] have removed all Airfone handsets from their planes.  Verizon will continue to provide service on 3,400 private and government aircraft.\n\nOn December 28, 2007, Airfone announced it would discontinue service effective December 31, 2008 unless it successfully concludes negotiations with [[LiveTV]], an affiliate of [[JetBlue]], to take over the business on that date. On June 9, 2008, JetBlue announced that it would buy Verizon's Airfone service.  The sale of Verizon Airfone to LiveTV (JetBlue) was separate from the sale of the bandwidth that Verizon Airfone used for its operations. In another transaction, LiveTV acquired about 1/3 of the original Airfone bandwidth from the FCC.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idUSN0944090420080609?feedType=RSS&feedName=technologyNews JetBlue LiveTV to buy Verizon's Airfone network],\" ''[[Reuters]]''</ref>\n\n=== LiveTV continues in-flight voice for general aviation ===\nFor a time [[LiveTV]] offered, nationwide, mobile telephone style voice service to general aviation aircraft. This service was identical to the original Verizon Airfone service. However, because of the change of [[bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]] allocation, all of the existing Airfone transceivers in the aircraft were required to be replaced.\n<ref>\"[http://www.LiveTV.net LiveTV home page],\" ''[[LiveTV]]''</ref>\n\n=== Sale to Aircell ===\nIn April 2013, [[Aircell]] acquired LiveTV's Airfone business unit, and announced that in order to support capacity-expansion for the Gogo Biz<ref>[http://www.gogoair.com/ Gogo Biz\u00ae]</ref> in-flight Internet service, the Airfone service was permanently decommissioned on December 31, 2013.<ref>[http://www.aircell.com/press-room/aircell-completes-airfone-acquisition Aircell Completes Airfone Acquisition, Broomfield, CO \u2013 April 15, 2013]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051214034539/http://www22.verizon.com/airfone/ Verizon Airfone website]\n* [http://www.crn.com/sections/special/hof/hof00.jhtml;jsessionid=MNEYAXE4IIIMUQSNDBCSKH0CJUMEKJVN?articleId=18834873&_requestid=355306  Jack Goeken By Larry Hooper From the November 08, 2000 CRN]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.airfonetransition.com/ Airfone Transition web page.]\n* [http://www.aircell.com/press-room/aircell-completes-airfone-acquisition Aircell statement on transition.]\n* [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-05-07/business/chi-gogo-buys-airfone-to-boost-inflight-wifi-20120507_1_airfone-wi-fi-gogo ''Chicago Tribune'' article on GoGo purchase of Airfone assets.]\n\n[[Category:Telephone services]]\n[[Category:Avionics]]\n[[Category:Mobile radio telephone systems]]\n[[Category:Verizon Communications]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Air-ground radiotelephone service}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2009}}\n{{Missing information|technical details and payment methods|date=March 2013}}\n}}\n\n'''Airfone''' was an [[air-ground radiotelephone service]] developed by [[MCI Communications|MCI]] founder [[John D. Goeken]], and operated under the names ''Airfone'', ''GTE Airfone'', and [[Verizon]] Airfone. Airfone allowed passengers to make telephone calls (later including data modem service) in-flight. Airfone handsets were often located in the middle airliner seatbacks, with two handsets per row for 6-wide coach seating configurations, and more or less depending on the aircraft layout and fare class. First class cabins typically had one handset per seat. Some planes had one or more bulkhead mounted phone stations with cordless handsets that the passengers could use, instead of the multiple wired handsets.  Airfone phone calls were usually quite expensive compared to ground-based telephone calls, costing $3.99 per call and $4.99 per minute in 2006.\n\nThe original Airfone main office