ernunionalumni.com/history.htm|accessdate=2008-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207045921/http://www.westernunionalumni.com/history.htm|archive-date=2012-02-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Delta Air Lines]] offered the United States's first public air-to-ground telephone system with Airfone.\n\nThe first iteration of Airfone service only permitted air-to-ground calls and frequently dropped calls. A new generation dubbed GenStar was developed jointly by GTE and [[Teknekron Corporation#Successes|IEX Corp.]] in 1992. IEX developed the software, which ran on hardware built by [[Stratus Technologies#History|Stratus Computers]]. GenStar introduced the capacity for airborne nodes to also receive calls, and for connections to be [[Handover|handed over]] between ground cells as the aircraft moved through them, reducing dropped calls. Handsets also gained screens and jacks for fax transmissions.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Belden | first = Tom | title = New Phone System Reaches Passengers During Their Flights | work = The Philadelphia Inquirer | location = Philadelphia | accessdate = 2012-10-04 | date = 1993-12-20\n| url = http://articles.philly.com/1993-12-20/business/25940877_1_gte-airfone-new-phone-system-genstar }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | pages = 1F | last = Steinert-Threlkeld | first = Tom | title = GTE Airfone responds to higher calling | work = The Dallas Morning News | accessdate = 2012-10-04 | date = 1992-02-08 | url = http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/NewsBank/0ED3D219988FC03A/49A2E19BE58747EE91F5ACB8D85A7A48?s_lang }}</ref>\n\n===Demise===\nThe head of the Airfone division told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2004 that only two to three people use the Airfone service per flight.  In May and June 2006, the frequencies ([[Bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]]) over which Airfone operated were sold at auction by the [[U.S. Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) to two new licenseholders, [[Aircell]] and [[LiveTV]].<ref>[https://www.engadget.c